        'Mahatma Gandhi\'s arrival in India in 1915 introduced a revolutionary new method of struggle known as Satyagraha. This method had two fundamental principles: "satya" meaning truth, and "ahimsa" meaning non-violence. Gandhi believed that one could win any battle by standing firmly on the side of truth without using any physical force against the opponent. This was a powerful and unique weapon that no one had used before on such a massive scale.\n\nAfter travelling across India, Gandhi identified two main goals for the freedom struggle. His first goal was to end British rule and win complete independence for India. His second goal was equally important — to end the evil social and religious practices that were hurting Indian society, such as untouchability. He believed that a truly free India must be free both from foreign rule and from internal injustice. Using Satyagraha, he led millions of Indians in peaceful non-violent mass movements that ultimately forced the British to leave.',
